    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-26T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-26T18:00:00-05:00" n="488"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d488">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.85/2–2646: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in China</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-26T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 26, 1946—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>345. For General Marshall from Colonel Davis. The following is for your
                    information: Informal advice indicates no direct reply will be made to your
                    radio 234, dated 23 February. Enabling legislation now pending in Congress,
                    passage of which is necessary prerequisite to sale of six Liberties to Chinese,
                    provides that authority to make sale will rest with Maritime Commission, not
                    with War Department. Owning agency must make vessels to be sold available to
                    Maritime Commission before Maritime Commission can make disposition. Therefore,
                    procedure for sale of these six Liberties will include (<hi rend="italic"
                    >a</hi>) return of ships by War Department to WSA, (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)
                    declaration of ships as available for sale by War Shipping Administration, and
                        (<hi rend="italic">c</hi>) sale on <pb facs="0802" n="792" xml:id="pg_792"/>
                    terms provided in the Ships Sales Act<note n="49" xml:id="d488fn49">Proposed
                        legislation subsequently enacted; approved March 8, 1946, 60 Stat.
                        41.</note> by the Maritime Commission.</p>
                <p>War Department has authorized Wedemeyer to return the six Liberties to WSA at any
                    time such return may be necessary to consummate sale. Believe this constitutes
                    only War Department action necessary to expedite transaction. Your office here
                    is following matter with Maritime Commission. [Davis.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
